{{Politics of Latvia}}
An '''[[independence referendum]]''' was held in [[Latvian Soviet Socialist Republic|Latvia]] on 3 March 1991,<ref name=NS>[[Dieter Nohlen]] & Philip Stöver (2010) ''Elections in Europe: A data handbook'', p1122 {{ISBN|978-3-8329-5609-7}}</ref> alongside a similar referendum in the [[Estonian independence referendum, 1991|Republic of Estonia]]. Known as the "Popular Survey about the independence of the Republic of Latvia", voters were asked "are you in favour of a democratic and independent Republic of Latvia".<ref name=DN>Nohlen & Stöver, p1136</ref> It was approved by 74.9% of voters, with a turnout of 87.6%.<ref name=DN/> Latvian Republic civilians registered in Soviet Army units also had the right to vote in this poll.<ref>[http://www.likumi.lv/doc.php?id=65213 LATVIJAS REPUBLIKAS AUGSTĀKĀS PADOMES LĒMUMS Par kārtību, kādā notiek Latvijas iedzīvotāju aptauja]</ref>
The independence of Latvia was finally restored on August 21, 1991.
==Results== {| class=wikitable style=text-align:right !Choice !Votes !% |- |align=left|For||1,227,562||74.9 |- |align=left|Against||411,374||25.1 |- |align=left|Invalid/blank votes||27,192||– |- |align=left|'''Total'''||'''1,666,128'''||'''100''' |- |align=left|Registered voters/turnout||1,902,802||87.6 |- |align=left colspan=3|Source:<ref>[http://web.cvk.lv/pub/public/27555.html Central Election Commission of Latvia. ''Latvian independence poll''] (in Latvian)</ref> |}
==Comparison of results in all Baltic states== Similar independence referendums were also held in Estonia on 3 March 1991 and on 9 February in Lithuania. {| class="wikitable" ! !Latvia !Estonia !Lithuania |- |Registered voters/turnout |87.6 |82.9 |84.7 |- |For (%) |74.9 |78.4 |93.2 |- |Against (%) |25.1 |21.6 |6.8 |- |National minorities in 1991 (%) |48 |40 |20 |}
